What exactly is the problem you are trying to solve? I don't see anywhere in the nova code where the vsphere driver is imported directly. Nova should have a driver interface that allows nova to load the driver specified in nova.conf. Copying one package's source code on top of another package is not acceptable and will break uninstallability."}, {'account_id': 6876, 'date': '2019-02-05 16:21:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@colleen This patch is to address the import errors described in [1]. See the description and the comments in the bug report.

[1] https://bugzilla.suse.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1119622'}, {'account_id': 13770, 'date': '2019-02-12 19:54:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

@collen the point you bring up is valid, but this is not something new. Because of the way nova restricts which drives can be imported (the directory which the file containing the driver is hardcoded into nova source code (upstream nova source code). Thus in order for the driver to be available for nova it MUST be copied over to the nova directory. Again, this is not something new, its just the way nova works.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2019-02-13 10:45:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I tested out the package and it doesn't seem to have the uninstallability problems I was worried about. I don't like this pattern but searching through the nova docs I can see that there isn't a strong interface for out-of-tree drivers, so this may be the best we can do for now."}, {'account_id': 7102, 'date': '2019-02-13 11:48:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]

